{
  "doc_id": "46038",
  "text": "Among breast cancer subtypes, basal-like breast cancer has high stemness [CITATION_1] . A membrane-bound hyaluronan receptor CD44 is known as a factor for stemness [CITATION_2] . In humans, the CD44 gene has various isoforms that are generated by alternative splicing of 9 variant exons [CITATION_3] . The CD44 standard form has an extracellular ligandbinding region, a transmembrane region, and an intracellular region; however, this form does not contain variant exons. CD44 variant isoforms have insertions of variant exons between the extracellular and the transmembrane regions. The expressions of CD44 variant isoforms are used for cancer stem cell markers, as well as upregulation of CD44 expression [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . However, not all CD44 isoforms involved in stemness have been identified.",
